# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bob-lurie
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bob-lurie/1883-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1883 throughout the world.
[src:bob-lurie/1957-in-baseball-p01] The following are the baseball events of the year 1957 throughout the world.
[src:bob-lurie/1958-in-baseball-p01] The following are the baseball events of the year 1958 throughout the world.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] After serving for four years in the U.S.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] Navy during World War II, Rosen returned to become a stand-out for the Indians on both offense and defense.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] A four-time All-Star, he was the first rookie to lead the American League in home runs, going on to drive in 100 or more runs for five consecutive years and twice led the league in home runs and twice in runs batted in (RBIs).
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] Rosen was a member of the 1948 World Series winning team, and won the 1953 AL Most Valuable Player Award.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] Following two decades as a stockbroker after retirement from baseball, Rosen returned to the game as a top front office executive in the late 1970s, serving the New York Yankees, Houston Astros and San Francisco Giants variously as president, CEO, and general manager.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] Regarded as an executive who still thought like a player, he became the only former MVP to also earn baseball's Executive of the Year award.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] He was inducted into the Cleveland Guardians Hall of Fame in 2006.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] Rosen was born in Spartanburg, South Carolina, to Louis and Rose (née Levin) Rosen.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] His father left the family shortly thereafter, and Rosen's mother and grandmother moved the family to Miami, Florida, when he was 18 months old.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] Rosen suffered from asthma as a child, which prompted his family to move further south.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] While growing up, his two favorite baseball players were Lou Gehrig and Hank Greenberg.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] He attended Riverside Elementary School, Ada Merritt Junior High School, and then Miami Senior High School for a year before attending Florida Military Academy in St.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] Petersburg, Florida, on a boxing scholarship.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] After graduating from Florida Military Academy, Rosen enrolled in the University of Florida in Gainesville, Florida.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] He left the university after a semester to play minor league baseball in North Carolina.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] Rosen enlisted in 1942, and spent four years in the U.S.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] Navy fighting in the Pacific during World War II, delaying his professional baseball career.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] He navigated an assault boat in the Battle of Okinawa.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] He left the Navy as a lieutenant the following year, returning to baseball.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] Rosen played for the 1946 Pittsfield Electrics, where he was initially given a back-up role.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] Upon leading the Canadian–American League in home runs (16) and RBIs (86), while batting .323, however, he was bestowed his idol Hank Greenberg's nickname, "the Hebrew Hammer".
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] Rosen played for the Oklahoma City Indians of the Texas League in 1947, and had one of the finest individual seasons in league history.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] He won the Texas League Player of the Year Award.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] Rosen played for the New York Yankees' Kansas City Blues farm team in 1948.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] He was loaned to the Blues for the duration of the team's American Association season as part of a deal that sent reliever Charley Wensloff from the Yankees to the Indians.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] Rosen was named Rookie of the Year in the American Association for his play with the Blues.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] Rosen made his first appearance in the major leagues in 1947 at age 23.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] In 1948, Rosen played most of the year in minor leagues with the Kansas City Blues, before joining the Indians in September.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] He played in the 1948 World Series as a reserve behind regular third baseman Ken Keltner despite only playing five games during the season after the Indians requested his inclusion on the World Series roster.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] When Keltner was traded in 1950, Rosen took over as the Indians' third baseman, leading the American League in home runs with 37, hitting more than any previous American League rookie.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] It stood as the AL rookie record until Mark McGwire surpassed it in 1987.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] He homered in four straight games in June, a feat unmatched by an Indians rookie until Jason Kipnis in 2011.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] Rosen averaged a league-best homer every 15.0 at bats, and led the league as well in HBP (10).
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] He batted .287 and had 116 runs batted in, while finishing fifth in the league with 100 walks and a .543 slugging percentage.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] His 100 walks remained a team rookie record for a right-handed batter, through 2014.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] He also remained the most recent AL rookie to record at least 100 walks until Aaron Judge in 2017.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] Despite his home run title, he finished 17th in the American League MVP Award voting.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] In 1951 Rosen led the league in games played, and was fifth in the league in RBIs (102), extra-base hits (55), and walks (85).
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] Rosen hit four grand slams, a team season record that was not broken until Travis Hafner hit five in 2006.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] Rosen led the American League with 105 RBIs and 297 total bases in 1952.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] He also was third in the league in runs (101) and slugging percentage (.524), fifth in hits (171) and doubles (32), sixth in home runs (28), and seventh in batting average (.302).
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] On April 29, he matched the then team record of three home runs in one game, which was surpassed only when Rocky Colavito tied the Major League single-game record with four home runs on June 10, 1959.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] Rosen came in tenth in the American League MVP Award voting.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] In 1953, Rosen led the American League in home runs (43), runs batted in (145), runs (115), slugging percentage (.613), and total bases (367).
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] He also came in second in OBP, and third in hits (201), and tied for eighth in stolen bases.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] Defensively, he had the best range factor of all third basemen in the league (3.32), and led it in assists (338) and double plays (38).
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] His RBI total is still the most for an Indians third baseman, through 2017, and is fourth most for any Indian in a season.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] He batted .336, and missed winning the batting title – and with it the Triple Crown – on the last day of the season, by just over one percentage point.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] He was elected American League MVP by a unanimous vote, the first to be elected unanimously since the original "Hebrew Hammer", Hank Greenberg.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] In the 2001 edition of the *New Historical Baseball Abstract*, Bill James named Rosen's 1953 season the greatest ever by a third baseman.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] It is ranked 164th overall, and 48th best by a position player by Baseball-Reference.com as of Rosen's passing.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] In 1954 he hit an even .300, led the league in sacrifice flies with 11, was fourth in SLG (.506), and fifth in home runs (24), RBI (102), and OBP (.404).
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] He also hit consecutive home runs in the All-Star game despite a broken finger, earning him the game MVP.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] His five RBI in the game matched the record set by Ted Williams five years earlier, which still stood through the 2011 season.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] Hall of Fame manager Casey Stengel said of him: "That young feller, that feller's a ball player.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] Gets all the hits, gives you the hard tag in the field.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] That feller's a real competitor, you bet your sweet curse life." Cleveland won the pennant, but lost the World Series.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] In 1955 Rosen finished in the top ten in the league in at-bats per home run, walks, and sacrifice flies.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] Rosen appeared on the cover of *Sports Illustrated* in 1955.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] By 1956, back problems and leg injuries caught up with Rosen and he retired at age 32 at the end of the season.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] After retiring in 1956 Rosen pursued a career as a stockbroker, an occupation he held for the next 22 years.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] In 1973, Rosen left investments for Caesars Palace in Las Vegas, where he worked for five years.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] In 1978, Rosen became president and CEO of the New York Yankees.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] They won the 1978 World Series, but Rosen quit on July 19, 1979.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] Tommy John thought he left because owner George Steinbrenner had replaced Bob Lemon, a friend of Rosen's, with Billy Martin as the team manager a month before.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] Rosen served as a supervisor of credit operations at Bally's in Atlantic City before a loan going sour led to him resigning.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] Rosen then served as team president and general manager of the Houston Astros (1980–1985).
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] Rosen was hired two weeks after the 1980 season ended for the Astros by owner John McMullen, who in a controversial decision had fired Tal Smith despite forming a core that won the National League West title.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] From 1981 to 1985, the Astros went 386–372 with one playoff appearance [1981 NLDS] before a mutual agreement was reached by both as Rosen departed in September 1985.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] He was hired as president and general manager by Bob Lurie of the San Francisco Giants a week after he left the Astros, where he would serve until 1992.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] Notably, one of his first actions was to remove the television and stereo systems from Candlestick Park as a means to have the players totally focused on baseball.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] Roger Craig was retained as manager after taking over for Jim Davenport in September, complete with Rosen allowing Craig full control.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] Through acquisitions (such as Rick Reuschel) and promoting draft picks such as Will Clark, Rosen and his maneuvering brought San Francisco from last place in 1985 to the NL West title in 1987 and the National League pennant in 1989, earning him the National League Executive of the Year honors.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] Regarded as a GM who still thought like a player, he became the only MVP in history to also earn the top executive award.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] The Giants went 589–475 with Rosen as general manager.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] An announcement of the sale of the team by Lurie in June 1992 (which was bought by Peter Magowan in January 1993 after a scuttled sale to Florida investors) precluded the departure of Rosen, who resigned in late November 1992.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] Quinn fired Craig as manager the following month.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] To replace him, Quinn named Dusty Baker as manager; Rosen had hired him to serve as first base coach of the Giants in 1988 after telling him he would be better suited for the role rather than assistant general manager.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] In 1979, Rosen appeared with Spec Richardson (general manager of the San Francisco Giants) in a television commercial entitled "Baseball Executives" for Miller Lite, as one of the commercials in the legendary "Great Taste, Less Filling" advertising campaign.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] The commercial ran heavily during the summer of 1979 along with every game of the World Series that year.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] Rosen's wife of 19 years, the former Teresa Ann Blumberg, died on May 3, 1971.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] He remarried to second wife, Rita (née Kallman) several years later.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] He had three sons, and a stepson and stepdaughter.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] Rosen occasionally consulted for baseball teams, including a stint with the Yankees as special assistant to the general manager in 2001 and 2002.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] He was featured in the 2010 movie narrated by Dustin Hoffman, *Jews and Baseball: An American Love Story*.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] Rosen died on March 13, 2015, in Rancho Mirage, California.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] He was tough, an amateur boxer, and had a reputation for standing up to anyone who dared insult his ancestry.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] While some reports have him commenting that, as a minor leaguer, he wished his name were something less obviously Jewish, he is later known to have remarked that he wished it were *more* Jewish—something like Rosenstein.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] When Ed Sullivan, himself a Catholic with a Jewish wife, suggested that Rosen might be Catholic, pointing to his habit of drawing a "cross" in the dirt with his bat, Rosen said the mark was an "x" and told Sullivan he wished his name were more Jewish so he wouldn't be mistaken for Catholic.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] Once a White Sox opponent called him a "Jew bastard".
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] Sox pitcher Saul Rogovin, also Jewish, remembered an angry Rosen striding belligerently to the dugout and challenging the "son of a bitch" to a fight.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] Rosen challenged another opposing player who had "slurred [his] religion" to fight him under the stands.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] And during a game, when Red Sox bench player Matt Batts taunted Rosen with antisemitic names, Rosen called time and left his position on the field to confront Batts.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] Hank Greenberg recalled that Rosen "want[ed] to go into the stands and murder" fans who hurled antisemitic insults at him.
[src:bob-lurie/al-rosen] A 2010 documentary, *Jews and Baseball: An American Love Story*, highlighted Rosen, who in it is frank about how he dealt with antisemitism: "There's a time that you let it be known that enough is enough. ...
[src:bob-lurie/alternative-golf-association] The **Alternative Golf Association**, also known as **Flogton** ("not golf" backwards), was formed in 2011 by a group of Silicon Valley executives.
[src:bob-lurie/alternative-golf-association] It tried to encourage golf participation by relaxing or ignoring traditional rules to reduce player frustration.
[src:bob-lurie/alternative-golf-association] According to the National Golf Foundation, there was a decline in the number of golfers and rounds played in 2011 compared to 2005.
[src:bob-lurie/alternative-golf-association] Flogton aspired to stimulate golf as snowboarding helped skiing.
[src:bob-lurie/alternative-golf-association] Gallagher (CEO), Scott McNealy (Commissioner) and Bob Lurie were involved with Flogton.
[src:bob-lurie/alternative-golf-association] Flogton encouraged nonconforming equipment such as lubricant applied to club faces, wedges textured like cheese graters and Polara Golf Ultimate Straight balls.
[src:bob-lurie/andrew-freedman] Andrew Freedman was born in New York City on September 1, 1860; his family were middle-class German-Jewish immigrants.
[src:bob-lurie/andrew-freedman] 35, a public school in Lower Manhattan, and City College of New York.
[src:bob-lurie/andrew-freedman] In 1895, Freedman became the principal owner of the New York Giants of the National League (NL), purchasing a controlling interest in the club from Cornelius C.
[src:bob-lurie/andrew-freedman] Van Cott for approximately $53,000 ($2,051,100 in current dollar terms).
[src:bob-lurie/andrew-freedman] During his ownership of the team, Freedman drew the ire of many of his players for various fines and abuses.
[src:bob-lurie/andrew-freedman] In one incident, star pitcher Amos Rusie sat out the entire 1896 season during a feud with Freedman.
[src:bob-lurie/andrew-freedman] NL presidential candidate Al Spalding called Freedman an "impossibility in baseball", demanding that Freedman retire from the game.
[src:bob-lurie/andrew-freedman] Brush, principal owner of the Cincinnati Reds, Freedman purchased controlling interest in the Baltimore Orioles of the rival American League (AL) on July 17, 1902.
[src:bob-lurie/andrew-freedman] The Orioles were in significant debt, reportedly owing $12,000 ($446,538 in current dollar terms).
[src:bob-lurie/andrew-freedman] As a result, part-owner and team president John Mahon purchased shares in the team from players John McGraw, Joe Kelley, and Wilbert Robinson, becoming principal shareholder of the Orioles.
[src:bob-lurie/andrew-freedman] Mahon, with the controlling interest in the Orioles, comprising 201 of the team's 400 total shares, sold his shares to Freedman.
[src:bob-lurie/andrew-freedman] Upon taking control of the franchise, Freedman released the Orioles' best players from their contracts so that they could be signed by NL teams: Kelley and Cy Seymour signed with the Reds, while Joe McGinnity, John McGraw, Roger Bresnahan, Dan McGann, and Jack Cronin signed with the Giants.
[src:bob-lurie/andrew-freedman] American League president Ban Johnson, along with minority owners of the Orioles, took control of the Orioles franchise, which had to forfeit their game that day as they did not have enough players.
[src:bob-lurie/andrew-freedman] The Orioles relocated to New York City in 1903 and were renamed the Highlanders; since 1913, the franchise has been the New York Yankees.
[src:bob-lurie/andrew-freedman] At the end of September 1902, Freedman sold the Giants to Brush.
[src:bob-lurie/andrew-freedman] Freedman took over the Manhattan Athletic Club, which fell into receivership in 1893, as its receiver.
[src:bob-lurie/andrew-freedman] He was a director of the Interborough Rapid Transit Company (IRT).
[src:bob-lurie/andrew-freedman] He first became involved in IRT when John B.
[src:bob-lurie/andrew-freedman] Freedman reported that he invested $1.7 million ($63,259,615 in current dollar terms) in the company in 1901 and 1902.
[src:bob-lurie/andrew-freedman] He also served on the board of directors of the Wright Company, established in 1909 to market the Wright brothers' airplanes in the United States.
[src:bob-lurie/andrew-freedman] Freedman owned an ice yacht, named "Haze", which won a pennant race in North Shrewsbury, New Jersey.
[src:bob-lurie/andrew-freedman] Freedman died in New York City on December 4, 1915, following a nervous breakdown.
[src:bob-lurie/andrew-freedman] His estate was worth over $4 million ($127,302,632 in current dollar terms).
[src:bob-lurie/andrew-freedman] Samuel Untermyer served as executor of the estate.
[src:bob-lurie/andrew-freedman] In his will, Freedman bequeathed money to build the Andrew Freedman Home at 1125 Grand Concourse in The Bronx.
[src:bob-lurie/andrew-freedman] The home was initially intended to serve as a retirement home specifically for wealthy people who lost their fortunes.
[src:bob-lurie/andrew-freedman] Plans were filed in 1922 to build the home as a four-story brick building, with the cost of construction estimated at $500,000 ($9,617,296 in current dollar terms).
[src:bob-lurie/andrew-freedman] The building cost approximately $1 million ($18,786,408 in current dollar terms) and opened in 1924.
[src:bob-lurie/andrew-freedman] The Andrew Freedman Home was named a New York City Designated Landmark in 1992.
[src:bob-lurie/atlee-hammaker] Hammaker was born in Carmel-by-the-Sea, California, on January 24, 1958, the son of Miyake and Charles Hammaker.
[src:bob-lurie/atlee-hammaker] A middle child, he has one older brother, Aldine and one younger sister, Charlene.
[src:bob-lurie/atlee-hammaker] Hammaker grew up living in many different locations due to his father's career in the United States Army, and attended Mount Vernon High School in Fairfax County, Virginia, where he played basketball, football, and baseball.
[src:bob-lurie/atlee-hammaker] After suffering a knee injury in football his sophomore year, he began focusing on basketball.
[src:bob-lurie/atlee-hammaker] Hammaker received a full basketball scholarship to East Tennessee State University (ETSU) in Johnson City.
[src:bob-lurie/atlee-hammaker] After being talked to and convinced by the coaches at ETSU, Hammaker decided to change his focus to baseball.
[src:bob-lurie/atlee-hammaker] He attended a summer league in Alaska, and from there, was a first-round pick (21st overall) in the 1979 MLB draft by the Kansas City Royals.
[src:bob-lurie/atlee-hammaker] In 1983, Hammaker's best season, he led the National League with an ERA of 2.25, a WHIP of 1.039, BB/9IP of 1.67, and strikeout to walk ratio of 3.97.
[src:bob-lurie/atlee-hammaker] That year Hammaker won 10, lost 9, and made the National League All-Star team.
[src:bob-lurie/atlee-hammaker] Hammaker made the National League All-Star team in 1983, but did not fare well, surrendering seven earned runs in 0.2 inning pitched; and he gave up the only grand slam in All-Star Game history, to Fred Lynn.
[src:bob-lurie/atlee-hammaker] The American League prevailed 13–3 for their first win in twelve years.
[src:bob-lurie/atlee-hammaker] In Game 7 of the 1987 NLCS, Hammaker, pitching for San Francisco, gave up a three-run homer in the second inning to José Oquendo, a utility infielder who had hit only one home run that season.
[src:bob-lurie/atlee-hammaker] The Cardinals won 6–0 to advance to the World Series.
[src:bob-lurie/atlee-hammaker] While with the Giants, Hammaker and teammates Scott Garrelts, Dave Dravecky and Jeff Brantley became known as the "God Squad" because of their strong Christian faith.
[src:bob-lurie/atlee-hammaker] Forgoing the hard-partying lifestyle of many of their teammates, they preferred to hold Bible studies in their hotel rooms while on the road.
[src:bob-lurie/atlee-hammaker] Hammaker is married and lives in Knoxville, Tennessee, with his wife.
[src:bob-lurie/atlee-hammaker] His second oldest daughter, Jenna Hammaker-Gomes, is married to major league player Yan Gomes.
[src:bob-lurie/bob-lurie] Lurie was born to a Jewish family in San Francisco, the son of Babette (née Greenbaum) and Louis Lurie.
[src:bob-lurie/bob-lurie] In 1972, he took over the real estate company founded in 1922 by his father.
[src:bob-lurie/bob-lurie] The company built a number of properties along Montgomery Street over the years, including a building Bank of America bought and tore down for its world headquarters at 555 California Street.
[src:bob-lurie/bob-lurie] Many of these buildings are still owned by the company.
[src:bob-lurie/bob-lurie] In 1975, Giants owner Horace Stoneham agreed to sell the team to a group headed by the Labatt Brewing Company, which intended to move the team to Toronto.
[src:bob-lurie/bob-lurie] San Francisco Mayor George Moscone won an injunction to stop the sale and then persuaded Lurie, a Giants minority owner and board member, to put together a group that would buy the team and keep it in San Francisco.
[src:bob-lurie/bob-lurie] In February 1976, Lurie announced he was bidding to buy the Giants for $8 million.
[src:bob-lurie/bob-lurie] Lurie's original investment partner was former Texas Rangers owner Bob Short.
[src:bob-lurie/bob-lurie] Lurie insisted that since, unlike Short, he was a San Francisco resident, he should have the final say in operational and league matters.
[src:bob-lurie/bob-lurie] The other National League owners were concerned about Short's checkered tenure as owner of the Rangers and also insisted that Lurie be empowered to cast the Giants' vote at owners' meetings.
[src:bob-lurie/bob-lurie] Short backed out of the deal on March 2, 1976, just days before the start of spring training.
[src:bob-lurie/bob-lurie] Racing a league-imposed five-hour deadline, Lurie convinced Phoenix-based meat packer Bud Herseth to put up half the purchase price.
[src:bob-lurie/bob-lurie] The transaction was unanimously approved by the other National League owners later that day.
[src:bob-lurie/bob-lurie] Lurie held a 51 percent controlling interest and Herseth held the other 49 percent.
[src:bob-lurie/bob-lurie] Lurie said that while he and Herseth were "equal partners in operation," he would cast the team's vote in league matters.
[src:bob-lurie/bob-lurie] Lurie bought out Herseth three years later in spring 1979.
[src:bob-lurie/bob-lurie] Lurie tried to make improvements to Candlestick Park but concluded there was no way the Giants could succeed there.
[src:bob-lurie/bob-lurie] In 1987 and 1989, San Francisco voters rejected stadium referendums to build a new downtown park while a plan to improve the existing stadium failed by an even wider margin.
[src:bob-lurie/bob-lurie] Lurie looked to move the team to San Jose or Santa Clara, but voters there rejected stadium proposals.
[src:bob-lurie/bob-lurie] In June 1992, Lurie announced that he would sell the Giants, claiming that he could no longer sustain the financial losses that had accumulated over the last few years.
[src:bob-lurie/bob-lurie] When no credible offers surfaced from Bay Area interests, Lurie agreed to sell the Giants for $115 million to an ownership group headed by Tampa businessman Vince Naimoli with plans to move the club to St.
[src:bob-lurie/bob-lurie] The National League nixed the deal and pressured Lurie to sell to Bay Area investors.
[src:bob-lurie/bob-lurie] In an 11th-hour effort to save the team from moving, a group of local investors headed by Safeway Inc. chairman Peter Magowan offered Lurie $100 million.
[src:bob-lurie/bob-lurie] Since selling the Giants, Lurie has focused on his real estate firm, the Lurie Co.
[src:bob-lurie/bob-lurie] He is also involved in various philanthropic activities, which include the $20 million Louis R.
[src:bob-lurie/bob-lurie] Lurie is an adviser of the Alternative Golf Association.
